{"key":"post-13082018","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13082018</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;uninc4life2010 said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I don't mist, the tub stays pretty humidifyed by its self.&amp;nbsp; I have six 2 in diameter holes drilled in the tubs, which are stuffed with polyfill to help prevent contams from entering.&amp;nbsp; They get plenty of light, so its all good.&amp;nbsp; The monotubs were left to coloinze for 10 days, the standard amount of time for a mono.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This&amp;nbsp; has always intrigued me.&amp;nbsp; How does one suppose the polyfill going to prevent contaminants from entering when the lids on these tubs have a gap all the way around?&amp;nbsp; In fact, the only purpose of the polyfill is to hold a high CO2 level during colonization.&amp;nbsp; You're recommended to remove it for fruiting to get fresh air.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Misting is not for humidity.&amp;nbsp; It's to replace the moisture lost from the substrate due to the correct level of air exchange.&amp;nbsp; Once you remove the polyfill, you'll need to mist.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;How are you getting fresh air and light in a closet?&amp;nbsp; It does no good to have a fan if it just blows the same stale air.&amp;nbsp; In addition, I doubt your substrate fully colonized in ten days.&amp;nbsp; Even if it did, all substrates benefit from at least a week after full colonization before exposing to fruiting conditions.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13082060</next>\n<prev>13082008</prev>\n<first>13081239</first>\n<last>13089104</last>\n<when>1282401493</when>\n<utime>08/21/10 05:38 PM</utime>\n</post>"}